Re: Security

Bitcointalk

2010-07-10 12:58:02 UTC - [11]Original Post

   Iʼll start thinking about how to do this.
   At the moment, you can kind of use -connect.  You can use -connect to
   make it connect to local computers on your LAN, like
   -connect=192.168.0.100.  If you start it out blank and donʼt let it
   connect to the main network, the difficulty is still at the original
   low difficulty.  If youʼve port-forwarded though, then outside nodes
   might still connect inward to you.
   With -connect it still uses IRC, do you think it shouldnʼt get on IRC
   when youʼre telling it to only connect to specific nodes with
   -connect?  The main scenario for -connect is where you have a server
   farm, with two connected to the network and the rest connected to the
   first two.  In that case, you wouldnʼt want the -connect computers on
   IRC.
   void ThreadIRCSeed(void* parg)
   {
       if (mapArgs.count("-connect"))
           return;
   [12]Previous | [13]Back | [14]Next
